## Code Implementation Guidelines

### Styling & Design System

- Use `styled-components` for reusable styled components when appropriate.
- Use inline styles with style objects (`style={{ ... }}`) for component-specific styling.
- Always use the design system tokens:
  - `asciiColors` for colors (background, foreground, muted, border, accent - navy blue)
  - `theme` for spacing, fonts, borderRadius, shadows, transitions
  - Font family: `'Consolas'` (monospace) for all text elements
- Maintain a monochromatic design palette: white, black, gray, and navy blue (`#1e40af`) for accents only.
- **IMPORTANT**: DO NOT use `asciiColors.success`, `asciiColors.warning`, or `asciiColors.danger` - these violate the monochromatic palette. Use gray variations or navy blue for states instead.
- Use `borderRadius: 2` for all rounded corners (minimal, ASCII-style).
- Use `1px solid` borders for normal elements, `2px solid` for highlighted/active elements.
- Avoid colorful backgrounds - use only `asciiColors.background` (white) and `asciiColors.backgroundSoft` (light gray).

### React Patterns

- Use functional components with hooks: `useState`, `useEffect`, `useCallback`, `useMemo`, `useRef`.
- Use early returns whenever possible to make the code more readable.
- Use `useCallback` for event handlers and functions passed as props to prevent unnecessary re-renders.
- Use `useMemo` for expensive computations.
- Use `useRef` for DOM references and mounting flags (`isMountedRef`).
- Always clean up effects (return cleanup functions in `useEffect`).

### Naming Conventions

- Use descriptive variable and function/const names.
- Use `const` instead of `function` declarations: `const fetchData = () => {}`.
- Event handlers can use descriptive names without mandatory prefixes (e.g., `toggleUserExpansion`, `fetchSecurityData`, `handleClick` when appropriate).
- Use PascalCase for component names.
- Use camelCase for variables, functions, and props.

### Accessibility

- Implement accessibility features on interactive elements.
- Use semantic HTML elements (`<button>`, `<nav>`, `<main>`, etc.) instead of `<div>` for interactive elements.
- Add `aria-label` for screen readers when needed.
- Add `tabIndex={0}` for keyboard navigation on custom interactive elements.
- Add `onKeyDown` handlers for keyboard interactions (Enter, Space keys).
- Provide focus states with visible outlines.

### Code Organization

- Group related functionality together.
- Place helper functions above the main component.
- Use JSDoc comments for complex functions: `/** Description */`.
- Keep components focused and single-purpose.
- Extract reusable logic into custom hooks when appropriate.

### TypeScript

- Define types/interfaces for props and complex data structures.
- Use type inference when types are obvious.
- Avoid `any` - use proper types or `unknown` when necessary.

### Performance & Best Practices

- Avoid unnecessary re-renders with proper memoization.
- Don't use auto-refresh intervals unless explicitly requested.
- Keep transitions subtle (0.15s ease) for hover and interaction states.
- Use consistent spacing from `theme.spacing` (xs, sm, md, lg, xl).

### Metrics & Cards

- Metrics MUST be displayed as cards with proper card styling (not just panels)
- Card structure: title (small, muted text), value (large, bold), optional subtitle
- Cards should have: padding, border (`1px solid ${asciiColors.border}`), borderRadius: 2, background
- Use only monochromatic colors in metric cards (white, black, gray) - no accent colors
- If any element in a component doesn't align with the design system, review and adjust it

